=== ARCHITECTURE DECISIONS LOG ===
Project: Autonomous Self-Improving Quant System
Architect: Claude (Lead Architect, per CLAUDE.md §1)
Initialized: 2026-06-24

--------------------------------------------------------------------
[ADR-001] Language / Tech Stack
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Decision: Python 3 end-to-end (NumPy + Pandas + PyArrow).
Rationale:
  - Target is daily-bar SPY research, not sub-microsecond execution.
    Vectorized NumPy/Pandas backtests on ~5000 daily bars run in
    milliseconds — Rust/C++ would be premature optimization (CLAUDE.md §2).
  - Pandas gives fast iteration on alpha logic for the Maker.
  - NumPy gives clean, dependency-light risk math for the Checker.
Rejected:
  - Rust Maker: only justified at tick/HFT scale. Revisit if/when the
    system moves to intraday sub-second signals.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
[ADR-002] Data Layer
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Decision: Parquet (PyArrow) files under data/cache, sourced via yfinance.
Rationale:
  - Columnar, compressed, ~10x smaller and faster to load than CSV.
  - HDF5 / time-series DB rejected: overkill for single-asset daily data.
  - Local cache makes the loop deterministic and offline-repeatable.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
[ADR-003] Maker/Checker Isolation (CLAUDE.md §5)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Decision: Three-layer isolation.
  1. CODE boundary  - The neutral runner (backtests/runner.py) is the ONLY
     consumer of Maker output. checker/verify.py imports only
     shared.contract + checker.metrics; it never imports maker.*.
  2. DATA contract  - Communication is files only:
        maker  -> data/signals.parquet            (positions in [-1,1])
        runner -> backtests/results/backtest_results.json (OOS math output)
        checker-> checker/verdict.json             (pass/fail + reasons)
     The Checker physically receives only mathematical output, never code.
  3. PROCESS boundary - loop.py runs each stage as a separate subprocess;
     no shared memory between Maker and Checker.
  + Git worktree: the Maker mutates strategy logic on an isolated branch
    (worktree at ../quant_maker, branch `maker`), keeping experimental
    signal code off the verification mainline.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
[ADR-004] Success Criteria (CLAUDE.md §4, §6)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Decision: A strategy PASSES only if, on out-of-sample data:
    OOS Sharpe >= 1.2  AND  Max Drawdown <= 15%.
  - In-sample / OOS split: TRAIN_END = 2018-12-31 (OOS = 2019-present).
  - Defined centrally in shared/contract.py so Maker and Checker agree
    without coupling.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
[ADR-005] Directory Structure
--------------------------------------------------------------------
  maker/      - alpha strategies + signal generation (template + active)
  checker/    - risk metrics + verifier (reads JSON only)
  backtests/  - neutral engine + results/  (the isolation boundary)
  data/       - ingestion + parquet cache
  shared/     - the cross-cutting data contract (schemas + thresholds)
  logs/       - execution & failure logs
  loop.py     - orchestrator (subprocess-isolated stages)
  STATE.md    - live system state / loop memory

--------------------------------------------------------------------
[ADR-006] ^VIX as a risk signal (added iter 3, 2026-06-24)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Decision: The Maker may read ^VIX (SPY's own implied-volatility index) as an
  INPUT signal. The traded position remains 100% SPY; the Checker still verifies
  SPY OOS returns only. ^VIX is cached alongside SPY by data/ingest.py.
Rationale:
  - SPY-close-only Kalman signals have a robust OOS Sharpe ceiling ~1.15 (12
    rounds of search). Crossing the 1.2 gate required an orthogonal risk signal.
  - Rising implied vol front-runs equity drawdowns (leverage effect + vol
    clustering) — economically grounded, not data-mined. ^VIX is a richer SPY
    feature, not a different asset, so the single-asset architecture holds.
Rejected: VIX *level* gating (peaks at bottoms → sells the low); realized-vol
  targeting (shrinks size into recoveries). Only the Kalman VIX *slope* helps.

